# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1901-detroit-tigers-season
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1901-detroit-tigers-season/1894-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the year 1894 throughout the world.
[src:1901-detroit-tigers-season/1900-detroit-tigers-season] The **1900 Detroit Tigers season** was the Tigers' first in the American League, which received recognition as a major league one year later in 1901.
[src:1901-detroit-tigers-season/1900-detroit-tigers-season] The Tigers finished in fourth place out of eight teams with a record of 71–67, 12+1⁄2 games behind Charles Comiskey's Chicago White Stockings.
[src:1901-detroit-tigers-season/1900-detroit-tigers-season] Detroit's home games were played at Bennett Park.
[src:1901-detroit-tigers-season/1900-detroit-tigers-season] Outfielder Dick Harley led the team with a .325 batting average, 77 runs scored, and 47 stolen bases.
[src:1901-detroit-tigers-season/1900-detroit-tigers-season] Sport McAllister led in slugging percentage (.383), and Frank Dillon led in extra-base hits (30).
[src:1901-detroit-tigers-season/1900-detroit-tigers-season] Roscoe Miller led the team with a 19–9 win-loss record for a .679 win percentage.
[src:1901-detroit-tigers-season/1900-detroit-tigers-season] Jack Cronin led in innings pitched (372) and strikeouts (121).
[src:1901-detroit-tigers-season/1900-detroit-tigers-season] Burns and George Stallings had spent large sums of money for "releases of star players" and had paid "major league salaries" to the majority of the players.
[src:1901-detroit-tigers-season/1901-baltimore-orioles-season] The 1901 Baltimore Orioles season finished with the Orioles in 5th in the American League with a record of 68–65.
[src:1901-detroit-tigers-season/1901-baltimore-orioles-season] The team was managed by John McGraw and played at Oriole Park.
[src:1901-detroit-tigers-season/1901-boston-americans-season] The **1901 Boston Americans season** was the first season for the professional baseball franchise that later became known as the Boston Red Sox, and the first season of play for the American League (AL).
[src:1901-detroit-tigers-season/1901-boston-americans-season] It resulted in the Americans finishing second in the AL with a record of 79 wins and 57 losses, four games behind the Chicago White Stockings.
[src:1901-detroit-tigers-season/1901-boston-americans-season] The team was managed by Jimmy Collins and played its home games at Huntington Avenue Grounds.
[src:1901-detroit-tigers-season/1901-boston-americans-season] On February 11, Jimmy Collins, third baseman for the National League Boston Beaneaters became the first player under contract for the Boston Americans after being offered a contract of $4000 with the added ability to sign subsequent players to contracts.
[src:1901-detroit-tigers-season/1901-boston-americans-season] Collins was joined on March 4 by the outfielder Chick Stahl, who was also from the Beaneaters.
[src:1901-detroit-tigers-season/1901-boston-americans-season] Defecting with Stahl and Collins was the outfielder Buck Freeman.
[src:1901-detroit-tigers-season/1901-boston-americans-season] Yet perhaps the most important signing was that of the 34 year old St.
[src:1901-detroit-tigers-season/1901-boston-americans-season] Louis Cardinals pitcher Cy Young, who accepted a contract worth $3500 from the Boston Americans.
[src:1901-detroit-tigers-season/1901-boston-americans-season] Vital to the signing of Cy Young from the Cardinals was the signing of Cy Young's catcher in St.
[src:1901-detroit-tigers-season/1901-boston-americans-season] Louis, Lou Criger; the value that Young gave to Criger and that Criger gave to Young was so strong, that it is unlikely that Young would have signed for the Americans if Criger had not done so.
[src:1901-detroit-tigers-season/1901-boston-americans-season] Prior to the regular season, the team held spring training in Charlottesville, Virginia.
[src:1901-detroit-tigers-season/1901-boston-americans-season] The total attendance for the Red Sox was 289,448, the second most in the American League (behind the White Sox' 354,350) and more than the crosstown Boston Beaneaters' 146,502.
[src:1901-detroit-tigers-season/1901-boston-americans-season] The offense was led by Buck Freeman, who hit 12 home runs and had 114 RBIs while recording a .339 batting average.
[src:1901-detroit-tigers-season/1901-boston-americans-season] The pitching staff was led by Cy Young, who made 43 appearances (41 starts) and pitched 38 complete games with a 33–10 record and 1.62 ERA, while striking out 158 in 371+1⁄3 innings.
[src:1901-detroit-tigers-season/1901-boston-americans-season] The team had two games end in a tie; August 31 at Detroit Tigers and September 12 at Washington Senators.
[src:1901-detroit-tigers-season/1901-boston-americans-season] Tied games are not counted in league standings, but player statistics during tied games are counted.
[src:1901-detroit-tigers-season/1901-boston-americans-season] Cy Young led the league in ERA (1.62), shutouts (5; tied with Clark Griffith), strikeouts (158), and wins (33).
[src:1901-detroit-tigers-season/1901-boston-beaneaters-season] The **1901 Boston Beaneaters season** was the 31st season of the franchise.
[src:1901-detroit-tigers-season/1901-boston-beaneaters-season] The Beaneaters finished fifth in the National League with a record of 69–69.
[src:1901-detroit-tigers-season/1901-brooklyn-superbas-season] The **1901 Brooklyn Superbas** lost several players to the newly official major league, the American League.
[src:1901-detroit-tigers-season/1901-brooklyn-superbas-season] The Superbas finished third in the National League with a record of 79–57.
[src:1901-detroit-tigers-season/1901-chicago-orphans-season] The **1901 Chicago Orphans season** was the 30th season of the Chicago Orphans franchise, the 26th in the National League and the ninth at West Side Park.
[src:1901-detroit-tigers-season/1901-chicago-orphans-season] The Orphans finished sixth in the National League with a record of 53–86.
[src:1901-detroit-tigers-season/1901-chicago-orphans-season] The team was also known as the Remnants, due to many Orphans players leaving at the end of the 1900 season to join the upstart American League.
[src:1901-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] The **1901 Detroit Tigers season** was the Tigers' 2nd season in Major League Baseball.
[src:1901-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] The team was a charter member of the American League, which was originally formed as the minor-league Western League, of which it had also been a charter member.
[src:1901-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] The Tigers finished in third place with a record or 74–61, 8+1⁄2 games behind the Chicago White Stockings.
[src:1901-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] Most of Detroit's home games were played at Bennett Park, with Sunday games played at Burns Park due to Detroit's blue laws.
[src:1901-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] Roscoe Miller (23–13) led the team in wins and was the Tigers' first 20-game winner.
[src:1901-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] His performance headlined a strong pitching staff that had the third lowest ERA (3.30) in the American League.
[src:1901-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] Joe Yeager had an ERA of 2.61, for the second best Adjusted ERA+ in the AL, behind Cy Young.
[src:1901-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] The offense was not as strong however, scoring 741 runs – fifth among the eight teams in the league.
[src:1901-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] The team's best hitters were shortstop Kid Elberfeld (.308 average) and center fielder Jimmy Barrett (.293 average; 110 runs).
[src:1901-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] The Tigers had played their games at Bennett Park since 1896, but the graduation to a major league meant that there would now be games scheduled on Sundays, which was forbidden by Detroit's blue laws.
[src:1901-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] In order to avoid running afoul of this stricture, owner James D.
[src:1901-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] Burns built a ballpark on his own property in Springwells Township, Michigan just outside the Detroit city limits.
[src:1901-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] Named Burns Park, the Tigers would play their Sunday home games there for the 1901 and 1902 seasons.
[src:1901-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] During the 1901 season, Detroit attracted 259,430 fans at home and 238,100 on the road, for a total of 447,428.
[src:1901-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] Detroit ranked third behind Chicago and Boston in overall attendance.
